📒 My React Beginner Notes (From My my-spa Project)
1️⃣ What I Built

I built a Single Page Application (SPA) using React.

My app contains 5 pages:

🏠 Home

ℹ️ About

🖼️ Gallery

📞 Contact

🛒 Order Online

Instead of loading a new webpage each time, the app switches components instantly without refreshing.

That is what makes it a Single Page Application.

2️⃣ Tool I Used to Create the Project

I created the project with Vite.

Vite helped me:

Start a fast development server

Automatically reload the browser when code changes

Build the app for production later

Command I used:

npm run dev

This uses npm to start the development server.

3️⃣ Important React Files in My Project
index.html

This is the main HTML file.

It contains a special div:

<div id="root"></div>

React will place the entire application inside this div.

main.jsx

This is the entry point of the React app.

It starts React and loads the main component.

Example idea:

ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById("root")).render(<App />)

Meaning:

Start React
Render the App component
Put it inside the root div
App.jsx

This is the main controller of the UI.

It usually contains:

Navbar

Routes

Main layout

Example structure:

Navbar
Routes
Footer

Every page of the app starts from App.jsx.

4️⃣ Components (The Core of React)

React apps are built with components.

A component is simply a piece of the UI.

Examples from my project:

Home.jsx
About.jsx
Gallery.jsx
Contact.jsx
OrderOnline.jsx
Navbar.jsx

Instead of one huge file, React lets me split the interface into smaller reusable parts.

Think of components like Lego blocks.

5️⃣ Routing (How My Pages Work)

To switch between pages I used React Router.

Example idea:

/           → Home
/about      → About
/gallery    → Gallery
/contact    → Contact
/order      → Order Online

When I click a navigation link:

React Router switches components

The browser does NOT reload the page.

This makes the app fast and smooth.

6️⃣ Rendering (What React Does)

Rendering means:

Showing a component on the screen

Example:

<Home />

React converts it into real HTML and displays it in the browser.

When data changes:

React re-renders

This means it updates the UI automatically.

7️⃣ State (How React Remembers Data)

React components can store data using state.

Example concept:

cart items
form inputs
selected gallery image

When state changes:

React updates the UI automatically

This is why React apps feel interactive.

8️⃣ Why My SPA Is Fast

Traditional websites:

Click page
Browser reloads everything

React SPA:

Click page
React swaps components instantly

Only the changed part of the screen updates.

9️⃣ Development vs Deployment
Development

Running:

npm run dev

The site runs locally on my computer.

Example:

localhost:5173
Deployment

I deployed the app to Netlify.

Deployment means:

My project moved from my computer
to the internet

Now other people can open the site online.

🔑 My Personal Beginner Summary

From this project I learned:

React apps are built with components

Pages are controlled by React Router

Rendering shows components on the screen

State allows dynamic updates

Vite runs the development server

Deployment puts the app on the internet

✅ My first React project = a 5-page SPA with routing and deployment.

That’s actually a strong first step. 🚀
